h pragmatism. This fruitful hybridization emphasizes human–technology interrelationships, the role of embodiment and bodily skills, and the inherent multistability of technologies. In a radical argument, Ihde contends that philosophies, in the same way that various technologies contain an ever-shortening obsolescence, ought to have contingent use-lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aPhenomenology. 0aTechnologyxPhilosophy. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 4aScience Studies. 4aTechnology & Engineering. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Phenomenology.2bisacsh  aDewey.  aHusserl.  aembodiment.  ainstruments.  amultistability.  aphenomenology.  apostphenomenology.  apragmatism.  atechnologies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311072902340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082326963140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823269631423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823269631/original  a978-3-11-072902-3  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK